# Goals

---

## Runtime-G1 Checkpoint & Durability system enables long-running flows to survive crashes and resume without context loss
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** Relay-G1, Relay-G2

- [x] Every handoff produces a checkpoint with: git state, ledger state, handoff document, file manifest, token usage
- [x] Runs can resume from any checkpoint after process restart
- [x] Resume rehydrates the next agent from checkpoint (no chat history restored)
- [x] Rollback restores files, ledger, and state to a previous checkpoint
- [x] Fork creates a new run from an existing checkpoint with different parameters

Since agents "work longer rather than quicker," flows may run for hours or days. Checkpointing makes this safe. On resume, the next agent starts fresh from the Handoff Document — token cost is identical to continuous execution.
---

## Runtime-G2 Token Budgeting tracks and enforces per-step spend with cost analytics visible in Agents view
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** Relay-G1

- [x] Per-step token budgets with configurable limit, warning threshold, and strategy
- [x] Budget strategies: HardStop, EscalateModel, SummarizeContext, SkipOptional
- [x] Agents view shows real-time token spend and "savings vs parallel" estimates
- [x] Cumulative run budget prevents runaway costs
- [x] Cost analytics persist across checkpoints

Token budgeting makes cost a first-class constraint. The Agents view compares actual relay cost against estimated parallel-swarm cost to demonstrate savings.
---

## Runtime-G3 Boss-first execution: GSD mode runs autonomously with optional Check mode for gate review
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** Relay-G1

- [x] RelayMode enum exists: `GSD` (default) and `Check`
- [x] GSD mode: only GoalGate requires human approval; Design, Plan, Execution gates are auto
- [x] Check mode: every gate pauses for human review
- [x] Reviewer acts as internal quality auditor in GSD mode (no human gate)
- [x] Documenter compiles and delivers final Report as boss-facing product
- [x] Boss is interrupted only on ambiguity, blockage, budget exceed, or explicit Check mode

The human is the boss, not a coworker. The default behavior is autonomous execution. The boss gives one order and receives a Report. Human gates are opt-in, not mandatory.
